    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i'll try memory_profiler. but basically if it's a leak, it's like the memory just disappears or gets stolen by stuff i didn't even create, right? is that common in pandas when you're handling objects? it feels like something is just constantly nibbling away at my available ram in the background.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak isn't exactly like something *stealing* memory; it's more like objects you created are not being properly released by Python's garbage collector. In pandas, this is sometimes caused by keeping large intermediate copies of DataFrames or holding onto references to objects that are no longer needed. It's less about something external nibbling away and more about your code failing to tell Python, \"I'm done with this big piece of data now.\"",
      "source": "target",
